steps.text:
Consider the function \( f(x) = \begin{cases} 
1 & \text{if } x = \frac{1}{n} \text{ for some positive integer } n \\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases} \) on the interval \([0, 1]\). This function is discontinuous at points of the form \( \frac{1}{n} \) and zero everywhere else. The integral of this function over \([0, 1]\) is zero because the area under the curve is made up of infinitely many points of height 1 separated by intervals of length approaching zero, resulting in no net area. However, \( f(x) \neq 0 \) for infinitely many \( x \) in \([0, 1]\). Thus, a discontinuous function with all nonnegative terms can have an integral of zero without being identically zero.

